questions.text: Identify the structure that does not form the laryngeal skeleton:
questions.explanation:
Solution:

A A- Hyoid bone B- Thyroid cartilage C- Epiglottis D- Arytenoid cartilage Hyoid bone is not laryngeal cartilage. Hyoid bone forms part of the hypopharyngeal framework. Hypopharynx starts at the level of hyoid bone

Highyeild:

Laryngeal anatomy consists of the following cartilages for it’s structural framework: Larynx cartilages 3 Unpaired cartilages Epiglottis Thyroid Cricoid 3 Paired cartilages Arytenoid Corniculate Cuneiform

Random:

Explanation for incorrect options:- Option B Option C Option D A- Hyoid bone B- Thyroid cartilage C- Epiglottis D- Arytenoid cartilage Option B, C and D are laryngeal cartilage

Extraedge:

The hyoid bone (lingual bone or tongue-bone) is a horseshoe-shaped bone situated in the anterior midline of the neck between the chin and the thyroid cartilage. At rest, it lies between the base of the mandible and the third cervical vertebra. Unlike other bones, the hyoid is only distantly articulated to other bones by muscles or ligaments. It is the only bone in the human body that is not connected to any other bones nearby. The hyoid is anchored by muscles from the anterior, posterior and inferior directions, and aids in tongue movement and swallowing. The hyoid bone provides attachment to the muscles of the floor of the mouth and the tongue above, the larynx below, and the epiglottis and pharynx behind.

questions.text: Structure present behind the marked area is:
questions.explanation:
Solution:

Lesser wing of sphenoid The marked area given in the question is Pterion Pterion: H shaped suture Pterion is the name given to the region on the lateral aspect of the skull where four bones are joined The pterion is a craniometric point near the sphenoid fontanelle of the skull. It is a point of convergence of the sutures between the frontal, parietal, temporal (the squamous part) & greater wing of sphenoid. Deep to pterion, anterior branch of middle meningeal artery is present, on injury causes bleeding & a dangerous area in the skull. In the given options the Lesser wing of sphenoid is the best answer.

Highyeild:

Pterion involves three cranial sutures: Sphenoparietal suture Coronal suture Squamous suture

Random:

Explanation for incorrect options:- Option A- Post clinoid process Option C- Sella turcica Option D- Carotid canal The pterion is a craniometric point near the sphenoid fontanelle of the skull. It is a point of convergence of the sutures between the frontal, parietal, temporal (the squamous part) & greater wing of sphenoid. Deep to pterion, anterior branch of middle meningeal artery is present, on injury causes bleeding & a dangerous area in the skull. In the given options the Lesser wing of sphenoid is the best answer.

Extraedge:

Clinical edge: Pterion is a point of clinical significance – the skull is very thin at this point. In addition to being structurally weak due to being the point of union between several bones, it also lies over the anterior division of the middle meningeal artery. Fracture of the skull at this point can therefore disrupt the middle meningeal artery, leading to an extradural (epidural) haematoma.

The optic nerve , also known as the second cranial nerve, cranial nerve II, or simply CN II, is a paired cranial nerve that transmits visual information from the retina to the brain. In humans, the optic nerve is derived from optic stalks during the seventh week of development and is composed of retinal ganglion cell axons and glial cells; it extends from the optic disc to the optic chiasma and continues as the optic tract to the lateral geniculate nucleus, pretectal nuclei, and superior colliculus.

questions.text: Patient having paradoxical respiration, which of the following nerves will be affected:
questions.explanation:
Solution:

C Paradoxical respiration occurs due to the damage of the phrenic nerve, which is marked as D in the given Image . Laryngeal cavity

Highyeild:

In the neck, the phrenic nerve lies on the anterior surface of the anterior scalene muscle, passes over the dome of the pleura and enters the thorax posterior to the subclavian vein. The right and left phrenic nerves have a different course in the thorax but as a general rule they descend as lateral as possible whilst keeping in contact with the mediastinal pleura. Both travel anterior to the hilum/bronchus on their respective side.

Random:

Explanation for incorrect options:- The structures marked in the Image are: Right vagus nerve Left vagus nerve Recurrent laryngeal nerve Right phrenic nerve Paradoxical respiration occurs due to the damage of the phrenic nerve, which is marked as D in the given Image , therefore option A, B and D are incorrect answers. EXTRA EDGE

Extraedge:

The right Phrenic nerve descends in the thorax along the right side of the right brachiocephalic vein and the superior vena cava. It passes in front of the root of the right lung and runs along the right side of the pericardium, which separates the nerve from the right atrium. It then descends on the right side of the inferior vena cava to the diaphragm.Its terminal branches pass through the caval opening in the diaphragm to supply the central part of the peritoneum on its under aspect. The left Phrenic nerve descends in the thorax along the left side of the left subclavian artery. It crosses the left side of the aortic arch and here crosses the left side of the left Vagus nerve. It passes in front of the root of the left lung and then descends over the left surface of the pericardium which separates the nerve from the left ventricle. On reaching the diaphragm, the terminal branches pierce the muscle and supply the central part of the peritoneum on its under aspect.

questions.text: In the lymphoid organs listed below, reticular fibers are not found in which organ? Thymus Spleen Lymph node Bone marrow Select the correct answer from the given below code:
questions.explanation:
Solution:

1 only The correct answer is Thymus Thymic epithelial cells (also called epithelial-reticular cells or epitheliocytes), which make up the framework of the thymus. In the cortex as seen below, these cells are larger than the lymphocytes, and their nuclei contain prominent nucleoli. In the medulla, the thymic corpuscles or Hassall corpuscles, which are large collections of thymic epithelial cells. Thymic epithelial cells function to 1) form a blood-thymus barrier to shield developing thymocytes from exposure to antigens, 2) compartmentalize the thymus to sequester immature and mature thymocytes, in the cortex and medulla, respectively, 3) provide a structural and supportive framework for the developing thymocytes (the thymus lacks reticular fibers), and 4) present self and foreign antigens to developing thymocytes during positive and negative selection.

Highyeild:

Reticular fibers: Reticular connective tissue is a type of connective tissue with a network of reticular fibers, made of type III collagen. Reticular connective tissue is found around the kidney, liver, the spleen, and lymph nodes, Peyer's patches as well as in bone marrow. The fibers form a soft skeleton (stroma) to support the lymphoid organs. Adipose tissue is held together by reticular fibers.

Extraedge:

Reticular fibers, or reticulin is a type of fiber in connective tissue composed of type III collagen secreted by reticular cells. Reticular fibers crosslink to form a fine meshwork (reticulin). This network acts as a supporting mesh in soft tissues such as liver, bone marrow, and the tissues and organs of the lymphatic system.

questions.text: The histopathology specimen from autopsy of a 24 year old patient is shown in the Image below. The given structure is not found in:
questions.explanation:
Solution:

Epididymis The marked structure in the given Image is cilia. Among the given option epididymis is the only one not having cilia, It is lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium with stereocilia.

Highyeild:

Motile cilia are located on the epithelial cells of several internal organs such as lungs, trachea, digestive system, etc. They are also found on the protozoans such as paramecium and help them in locomotion. The non-motile cilia can be found in the dendritic knob of the olfactory neuron.

Random:

Explanation for incorrect options:- Option A. Oviduct (fallopian tube) Option C. Bronchi Option D. Ependyma Fallopian tube , Bronchi and Ependyma all are lined by ciliated epithelium.

Extraedge:

The body of the epididymis is a long convoluted duct The tubules are lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium in which there are tall columnar cells and shorter basal cells that do not reach the lumen. The columnar cells bear stereocilia Smooth muscles are present around each tubule, Clumps of spermatozoa are present in the lumen of the tubule.

Extraedge:

Gluteus maximus covers all of the gluteal muscles except for the anterosuperior third of the Gluteus medius. The ischial tuberosity can be felt deep to the lower part of the Gluteus maximus. When the thigh is flexed the lower border of Gluteus Maximus moves superiorly, exposing the ischial tuberosity subcutaneously (in sitting you sit on the ischial tuberosity, ischial bursae, subcutaneous fat, and skin.

Cross-sections are two-dimensional, axial views of gross anatomical structures seen in transverse planes. They are obtained by taking imaginary slices perpendicular to the main axis of organs, vessels, nerves, bones, soft tissue, or even the entire human body.

questions.text: Level of visceral pleura goes upto which of the following levels during deep inspiration:
questions.explanation:
Solution:

B During deep inspiration the lower border of the lung reaches level B anteriorly. The lower border of the lung extends till the 6th rib in the midclavicular line, 8th rib in mid axillary line and 10th rib in mid scapular line. During quiet breathing, the diaphragm moves about 1.5 cm. During deep breathing; however, it moves by 6-10 cm thus extending up to the level of the 6th rib or 11th thoracic vertebra on the right side. On full expiration, it extends up to 4th costal cartilage anteriorly, posteriorly up to the 8th vertebra. This corresponds to a line dividing the liver in upper 1/3rd and middle 1/3rd marked as B in the given Image .

Highyeild:

The diaphragm on the left side is generally lower than on the right side. The excursions of the diaphragm vary with position maximum in the supine position, lesser in an erect position, and least in sifting position. The lung is in the thoracic cavity and the liver lies in the abdominal cavity. The diaphragm separates the anterior surface of the lung from the liver at the level of a line drawn from the xiphisternal joint to the 8th rib laterally.

Random:

Explanation for incorrect options:- During deep inspiration the lower border of the lung reaches level B anteriorly. The lower border of the lung extends till the 6th rib in the midclavicular line, 8th rib in mid axillary line and 10th rib in mid scapular line. This corresponds to a line dividing the liver in upper 1/3rd and middle 1/3rd marked as B in the given Image, therefore option A,C and D are incorrect answers.

Extraedge:

The sternal angle in the majority of children from birth to 12 years of age is located level with the vertebral body of T4 .

Solution:

Opponens pollicis Origin: trapezium and transverse carpal ligament. Insertion: Metacarpal bone of the thumb on its radial side. Innervation: Recurrent branch of the median nerve, also ulnar nerve. Actions: Flexion of the thumb's metacarpal at the first carpometacarpal joint, which aids in opposition of the thumb. Arterial supply: Superficial palmar arch.

Highyeild:

Flexor pollicis brevis superficial head arises from the distal edge of the flexor retinaculum and the tubercle of the trapezium, the most lateral bone in the distal row of carpal bones. It passes along the radial side of the tendon of the flexor pollicis longus. The deeper (and medial) head "varies in size and may be absent." It arises from the trapezoid and capitate bones on the floor of the carpal tunnel, as well as the ligaments of the distal carpal row. Both heads become tendinous and insert together into the radial side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb; at the junction between the tendinous heads there is a sesamoid bone

Random:

Explanation for incorrect options:- Abductor pollicis longus is inserted on the side of the base. The first palmar interosseous muscle arises from the ulnar side of the base. Flexor pollicis brevis insert together into the radial side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb . Therefore Option A, B and D are incorrect answers.

Extraedge:

The superficial head of flexor pollicis brevis is usually innervated by the lateral terminal branch of the median nerve. The deep part is often innervated by the deep branch of the ulnar nerve (C8, T1).
